04073nam a22005535i 9780822382768DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223827687 a10.1515/97808223827682doi  a(DE-B1597)552376  a(OCoLC)1226678570  a(OCoLC)1136356072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR6019.O9bU6874 1999 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.9122211 aRickard, John S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJoyce's Book of Memory :bThe Mnemotechnic of Ulysses /cJohn S. Rickard. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (254 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Personal Memory and the Construction of the Self -- t2 The Past as Obstruction -- t3 Memory, Destiny, and the Limits of the Self -- t4 Joyce's Mnemotechnic: Textual Memory in Ulysses -- t5 Intertextual Memory -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: "Nausicaa" and The Golden Ass -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor James Joyce, perhaps the most crucial of all human faculties was memory. It represented both the central thread of identity and a looking glass into the past. It served as an avenue into other minds, an essential part of the process of literary composition and narration, and the connective tissue of cultural tradition. In Joyce's Book of Memory John S. Rickard demonstrates how Joyce's body of work-Ulysses in particular-operates as a "mnemotechnic," a technique for preserving and remembering personal, social, and cultural pasts.Offering a detailed reading of Joyce and his methods of writing, Rickard investigates the uses of memory in Ulysses and analyzes its role in the formation of personal identity. The importance of forgetting and repression, and the deadliness of nostalgia and habit in Joyce's paralyzed Dublin are also revealed. Noting the power of spontaneous, involuntary recollection, Rickard locates Joyce's mnemotechnic within its historical and philosophical contexts. As he examines how Joyce responded to competing intellectual paradigms, Rickard explores Ulysses' connection to medieval, modern, and (what would become) postmodern worldviews, as well as its display of tensions between notions of subjective and universal memory. Finally, Joyce's Book of Memory illustrates how Joyce distilled subjectivity, history, and cultural identity into a text that offers a panoramic view of the modern period.This book will interest students and scholars of Joyce, as well as others engaged in the study of modern and postmodern literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAutobiographical fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aAutobiographical memory in literature. 0aMemory in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382768423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382768.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles